'''Ubuntu Cola''' is a [[soft drink]] certified by [[The Fairtrade Foundation]]. Made with [[Fairtrade certification|Fairtrade]] sugar from [[Malawi]] and [[Zambia]], Ubuntu Cola is the first [[United Kingdom|UK]] cola to be Fairtrade certified.<ref name="SpecialityFood">{{ cite web | url = http://www.specialityfoodmagazine.com/site/index.php/site/view/uks_first_fairtrade_cola/ | title = UKâs first Fairtrade cola | publisher = Speciality Food Magazine | date = 2007-10-15 | accessdate = 2008-03-11 }}</ref> It is available for sale in the [[United Kingdom]], [[Sweden]], [[Norway]], [[Finland]], [[Ireland]], [[The Netherlands]], [[Belgium]], [[France]], [[Greece]], [[Italy]], [[Switzerland]] and online.<ref name="FoodBev">{{cite web | url = http://www.foodbev.com/interview/miranda-walker-ubuntu-cola | title = Miranda Walker, Ubuntu Cola | last = Weston | first = Shaun | publisher = FoodBev.com | date = 2010-04-29 }}</ref><ref name="UbuntuTrading">{{ cite web | url = http://www.ubuntu-trading.com | title = Ubuntu Trading (official website) | publisher = Ubuntu Trading Company Ltd | accessdate = 2009-09-17 }}</ref>
It is available in 330 ml cans, 500 ml [[Polyethylene terephthalate|PET]] plastic bottles, and 275 ml glass bottles.<ref name="UbuntuTrading" />
== Name ==
Like the [[Ubuntu (operating system)|Ubuntu]] computer operating system, the cola is named after the African philosophy of ''[[Ubuntu (philosophy)|Ubuntu]]'', which means ''humanity or fellow feeling; kindness'',<ref>{{ cite web | url = http://www.ubuntu-trading.com/we-are-ubuntu | title = We Are Ubuntu | publisher = Ubuntu Trading Company Ltd | accessdate = 2010-07-23 }}</ref> but otherwise there is no connection between the two. Moreover, although the Ubuntu OS is [[free and open source software]], Ubuntu Cola should not be confused with "[[open source]]" colas such as [[OpenCola (drink)|OpenCola]].
== Fairtrade ==
Ubuntu Cola's [[sugar]] is sourced from [[Fairtrade certification|Fairtrade]] [[worker cooperative]]s in [[Kasinthula]], [[Malawi]] and Kaleya, [[Zambia]]. Farmers who are members of the Fairtrade cooperative at Kasinthula receive an income of $4 a day, which is six times the [[national average income]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ubuntu-trading.com/we-are-ubuntu/ubuntu-in-malawi |title=Ubuntu in Malawi |publisher=Ubuntu-trading.com |date= |accessdate=2009-08-06}}</ref>
